WEBVTT

00:01.139 --> 00:03.210
[spirited music]

00:03.244 --> 00:05.246
- Welcome to the enchanted,

00:05.281 --> 00:08.525
seldom visited wonderland
of Asturias.

00:08.560 --> 00:10.079
♪♪

00:10.113 --> 00:12.564
That's in Spain,
if you didn't know,

00:12.598 --> 00:14.152
and, of course,
because it's Spain,

00:14.186 --> 00:15.843
I did not come here alone.

00:15.877 --> 00:16.913
- [laughs]

00:16.947 --> 00:19.053
- I came here
with a good friend,

00:19.088 --> 00:20.054
great chef.

00:20.089 --> 00:21.607
He's a complicated man.

00:21.642 --> 00:24.231
Nobody understands him
but his woman.

00:24.265 --> 00:26.198
And I'm not talking
about John Shaft.

00:26.233 --> 00:27.234
"Shut your mouth."

00:27.268 --> 00:30.168
I'm talking
about José Andrés...

00:30.202 --> 00:32.135
- Yeah, another beer.
Um, wide.

00:32.170 --> 00:34.655
Shit, Anthony's waiting!

00:34.689 --> 00:38.486
- Only chef
in the history of America

00:38.521 --> 00:42.594
ever to be sued
by a sitting president.

00:42.628 --> 00:45.252
I'm so proud of him.

00:45.286 --> 00:46.253
[rock music]

00:46.287 --> 00:47.771
- ♪ I took a walk

00:47.806 --> 00:52.121
♪ Through this
beautiful world ♪

00:52.155 --> 00:54.123
♪ Felt the cool rain

00:54.157 --> 00:57.333
♪ On my shoulder

00:57.367 --> 00:59.266
♪Found something good

00:59.300 --> 01:03.615
♪ In this beautiful world

01:03.649 --> 01:05.513
♪ I felt the rain

01:05.548 --> 01:07.722
♪ Getting colder

01:07.757 --> 01:09.517
♪

01:09.552 --> 01:12.589
♪Sha la la la la

01:12.624 --> 01:15.592
♪ Sha la la la la la

01:15.627 --> 01:18.492
♪ Sha la la la la

01:18.526 --> 01:23.566
♪ Sha la la la la la la

01:27.535 --> 01:30.504
[soft ambient music]

01:30.538 --> 01:37.476
♪

01:42.516 --> 01:44.207
- You know, sometimes
we have a hard time leaving

01:44.242 --> 01:46.934
the comfort of the known...

01:46.968 --> 01:54.114
♪

01:56.840 --> 01:59.567
And we don't understand
that life only starts...

01:59.602 --> 02:02.363
♪

02:02.398 --> 02:05.711
At the edge of the unknown.

02:05.746 --> 02:08.507
♪

02:08.542 --> 02:10.889
That's when life starts.

02:15.307 --> 02:16.515
[children chattering]

02:16.550 --> 02:19.518
[soft guitar music]

02:19.553 --> 02:22.935
♪

02:22.970 --> 02:25.938
[smooth bass and guitar music]

02:25.973 --> 02:28.907
♪

02:28.941 --> 02:31.910
[speaking Spanish]

02:31.944 --> 02:38.710
♪

02:40.643 --> 02:42.438
I've been an immigrant
all my life...

02:42.472 --> 02:44.785
♪

02:44.819 --> 02:46.925
From Asturias to Catalonia,

02:46.959 --> 02:49.203
from Catalonia to Madrid.

02:49.238 --> 02:51.378
♪

02:51.412 --> 02:53.380
Then I landed in America.

02:53.414 --> 02:54.760
[laughter]

02:54.795 --> 02:58.212
I've lived in the States
more than 26 years of my life.

02:58.247 --> 03:01.250
More than half of my life,
I've been there.

03:01.284 --> 03:03.217
♪

03:03.252 --> 03:06.289
I think everybody should be

03:06.324 --> 03:08.947
always finding the place
they come from.

03:08.981 --> 03:10.673
♪

03:10.707 --> 03:13.572
Asturias,
I left when I was five.

03:13.607 --> 03:15.781
A lot of people would not have
a lot of memories before five,

03:15.816 --> 03:17.231
but I do have them.

03:17.266 --> 03:20.234
And me, I always feel,
in Spain,

03:20.269 --> 03:22.961
like, so proud
that I am a Spaniard.

03:22.995 --> 03:24.618
That's why for me
coming back here

03:24.652 --> 03:26.930
is to understanding that,
yes, I'm from here,

03:26.965 --> 03:28.691
but they have to work hard
to belong.

03:28.725 --> 03:31.245
♪

03:31.280 --> 03:33.454
[shouts in Spanish]

03:33.489 --> 03:34.904
[affirmative shouting]

03:34.938 --> 03:38.287
[all singing in Spanish]

03:38.321 --> 03:44.983
♪

04:24.022 --> 04:25.644
[cheers and applause]

04:25.679 --> 04:27.819
[shouts in Spanish]

04:29.372 --> 04:31.443
Viva, Asturias!
all: Viva!

04:32.996 --> 04:34.688
- Astonishing.

04:34.722 --> 04:35.792
- [laughs]
- Unbelievable.

04:35.827 --> 04:37.553
- Well, I always
wanted to do it.

04:37.587 --> 04:38.933
[laughter]

04:38.968 --> 04:40.694
- Try that in New York.

04:40.728 --> 04:43.628
[laughter]

04:43.662 --> 04:45.388
So, a question:

04:45.423 --> 04:47.942
When you were a kid,
after you left here at age 5,

04:47.977 --> 04:48.943
how often did you visit?

04:48.978 --> 04:51.532
- It took me many, many years,

04:51.567 --> 04:54.017
almost like 12, 14 years
to come back.

04:54.052 --> 04:56.088
You know...

04:56.123 --> 04:57.642
because to me,
when I left so young,

04:57.676 --> 05:00.058
it's almost like meeting
a family you knew you had

05:00.092 --> 05:02.025
but you never met.

05:02.060 --> 05:03.958
Still, nothing beats
these moments.

05:03.993 --> 05:04.890
Always there's something
happening.

05:04.925 --> 05:06.616
- What do you eat here?
What's good here?

05:06.651 --> 05:07.962
- Everything.
- What do you eat?

05:07.997 --> 05:10.482
- Here right now is the season
of arbeyos.

05:10.517 --> 05:11.656
- Mm.

05:11.690 --> 05:13.105
- Which is the green peas.

05:13.140 --> 05:15.038
[dynamic guitar music]

05:15.073 --> 05:17.972
And right now is the season.

05:18.007 --> 05:21.459
And they love these green peas
here in season.

05:21.493 --> 05:23.599
And they serve them with ham.

05:23.633 --> 05:25.463
- Oh! This looks amazing.

05:25.497 --> 05:26.912
- Arbeyos.

05:26.947 --> 05:28.604
It's perfect.

05:28.638 --> 05:30.709
♪♪

05:30.744 --> 05:32.746
- Oh...
- Croquette.

05:32.780 --> 05:34.092
♪

05:34.126 --> 05:36.059
Everybody says that Asturias
has the best croquetas

05:36.094 --> 05:38.476
anywhere in Spain...

05:38.510 --> 05:39.925
- Really? Everybody says that?

05:39.960 --> 05:42.618
- Everybody, especially
the people in Asturias.

05:42.652 --> 05:43.929
- Yeah, I would guess.

05:43.964 --> 05:45.759
- [stammers]
[laughter]

05:45.793 --> 05:48.417
You see how creamy.

05:48.451 --> 05:49.935
Good taste.

05:49.970 --> 05:52.075
♪

05:52.110 --> 05:53.801
Ah, mussels.

05:53.836 --> 05:55.389
Perfect.
- Clams.

05:55.424 --> 05:57.736
- They make a great steak,
done with bleu cheese,

05:57.771 --> 05:59.807
right on top.

05:59.842 --> 06:01.706
Cabrales
on top of the steak.

06:01.740 --> 06:03.639
It's kind of the sauce happens
right on the plate.

06:03.673 --> 06:05.744
- Mm-hmm, okay.
- It's amazing.

06:05.779 --> 06:09.196
[speaking Spanish]

06:09.230 --> 06:12.026
♪

06:12.061 --> 06:13.821
- So, you want the whole cheese
to spoon--

06:13.856 --> 06:15.202
- Yeah.
It heavy, yeah? It heavy.

06:15.236 --> 06:17.066
It's spicy!
- [laughs]

06:17.100 --> 06:18.619
- Oh, no, I like spicy.

06:18.654 --> 06:21.139
- Oh, buh-buh,
buh-buh-buh-buh, no.

06:21.173 --> 06:24.142
[speaking Spanish]

06:24.176 --> 06:30.942
♪

06:30.976 --> 06:32.012
- José?

06:32.046 --> 06:33.807
♪

06:33.841 --> 06:35.498
- I love all the opinions.

06:35.533 --> 06:38.156
Everybody's highly opinionated,
as they should be.

06:38.190 --> 06:39.916
And nobody's gonna agree
with anybody,

06:39.951 --> 06:41.815
only because, why to agree?

06:41.849 --> 06:44.473
- Yeah, well, any place
where people argue about food

06:44.507 --> 06:45.991
is a good place.

06:46.026 --> 06:50.479
♪

06:50.513 --> 06:52.101
So, once a year,

06:52.135 --> 06:53.482
twice a year you come?

06:53.516 --> 06:55.553
- Yeah, well,
at least once a year,

06:55.587 --> 06:57.934
but sometimes, I only show up
for two, three hours.

06:57.969 --> 07:00.558
- Really?
- Yeah.

07:00.592 --> 07:02.663
I close the eyes,
I breathe in, breathe out,

07:02.698 --> 07:04.665
and, like, I'm home.

07:04.700 --> 07:07.012
Especially when I go
in the mountains.

07:07.047 --> 07:09.601
I love to be around people,
because I have a lot of energy,

07:09.636 --> 07:12.052
and I like to feed off of
the energy of the people too,

07:12.086 --> 07:13.950
and give energy away...
- Right.

07:13.985 --> 07:16.953
- But sometimes,
I need my moments of solitude.

07:16.988 --> 07:18.955
I know you like
moments of solitude too.

07:18.990 --> 07:21.820
They are powerful moments.

07:21.855 --> 07:24.789
- Yeah, but I'm not
walking up a mountain.

07:24.823 --> 07:26.756
- [stammers]
You'll see.

07:26.791 --> 07:28.620
And I'm gonna be taking you

07:28.655 --> 07:30.898
probably to the heart
of Asturias...

07:30.933 --> 07:32.003
- Oh, yeah?

07:32.037 --> 07:33.556
- It's where I feel
the happiest.

07:33.591 --> 07:34.661
- So I gotta hike up
a mountain?

07:34.695 --> 07:35.765
Is that what you're saying?

07:35.800 --> 07:37.802
- Well, I'll make a decent you.

07:37.836 --> 07:39.217
Okay, we need more cider.

07:39.251 --> 07:42.116
[speaking Spanish,
cider pouring]

07:42.151 --> 07:45.119
[slow pizzicato music]

07:45.154 --> 07:51.505
♪

07:54.059 --> 07:55.682
[laughs]

07:55.716 --> 07:58.719
[cheers and applause]

08:02.861 --> 08:05.830
[enchanting organ music]

08:05.864 --> 08:10.317
♪

08:10.351 --> 08:12.595
We're going deep, deep.

08:12.630 --> 08:14.563
♪

08:14.597 --> 08:17.324
- Through the mountain?

08:17.358 --> 08:20.292
- Through the mountain.

08:20.327 --> 08:22.156
It's always deep.

08:22.191 --> 08:27.265
♪

08:27.299 --> 08:29.785
Could you imagine,
less than 20 years ago,

08:29.819 --> 08:31.338
people had to walk
all the way to the top?

08:31.372 --> 08:33.754
- Wow.

08:33.789 --> 08:34.997
- [chuckles]

08:35.031 --> 08:37.033
♪

08:37.068 --> 08:38.034
- Wow.

08:38.069 --> 08:39.829
♪

08:39.864 --> 08:42.004
- [singing in Spanish]

08:42.038 --> 08:45.041
♪

08:45.076 --> 08:47.837
It's a hot day today.
- Yeah.

08:47.872 --> 08:49.321
♪

08:49.356 --> 08:54.844
- [singing in Spanish]

08:54.879 --> 09:01.886
♪

09:05.821 --> 09:08.133
I came overdressed, man.
- [groans]

09:08.168 --> 09:12.966
♪

09:13.000 --> 09:15.002
[sighs]
Jesus.

09:15.037 --> 09:16.866
- Okay, are you hungry now?

09:16.901 --> 09:18.178
- Oh, God, are we there?

09:18.212 --> 09:20.180
- [chuckles]
That's the town.

09:20.214 --> 09:22.665
- All right.

09:22.700 --> 09:24.633
- You're gonna see
what the people of the mountain

09:24.667 --> 09:26.911
used to eat.

09:26.945 --> 09:29.292
Beans.

09:29.327 --> 09:33.124
- Well, to quote the great
American poet Robert Frost:

09:33.158 --> 09:36.334
"Beans, beans,
the musical fruit.

09:36.368 --> 09:38.854
"The more you eat,
the more you toot.

09:38.888 --> 09:40.165
"The more you toot,
the better you feel,

09:40.200 --> 09:42.305
so eat some beans
with every meal."

09:42.340 --> 09:43.962
- [laughs]

09:43.997 --> 09:45.930
♪

09:45.964 --> 09:48.070
That's the reason
we're coming up here.

09:48.104 --> 09:51.004
- Yeah, it's beautiful.
- Yeah.

09:51.038 --> 09:52.971
- I expect to be accosted
by some Keebler Elves

09:53.006 --> 09:54.179
at any moment.

09:54.214 --> 09:56.354
♪ We welcome you
to Munchkin Land ♪

09:56.388 --> 09:58.321
♪ The Munchkin Land

09:58.356 --> 10:05.052
♪

10:08.228 --> 10:10.679
- It moves!

10:10.713 --> 10:12.646
[dog barking]

10:12.681 --> 10:14.096
Help!

10:14.130 --> 10:21.172
♪

10:34.703 --> 10:37.671
[slow guitar music]

10:37.706 --> 10:43.643
♪

10:46.887 --> 10:49.683
- You see, here in Asturias,
nothing is plentiful...

10:49.718 --> 10:50.926
♪

10:50.960 --> 10:52.168
And the people of Asturias,

10:52.203 --> 10:55.068
even in the hard times,
they know what to do...

10:55.102 --> 10:56.863
with nothing.

10:56.897 --> 10:58.968
♪

10:59.003 --> 11:00.142
I think Asturias
has been a land

11:00.176 --> 11:03.939
that with nothing
has able to do a lot,

11:03.973 --> 11:05.112
and that shows you
the character

11:05.147 --> 11:07.114
of the people of Asturias.

11:07.149 --> 11:12.775
♪

11:12.810 --> 11:16.261
[water rushing]

11:16.296 --> 11:19.264
[atmospheric music]

11:19.299 --> 11:26.202
♪

11:35.971 --> 11:37.248
- So, I'll tell you...

11:37.282 --> 11:39.526
five-hour hike up
the mountain, it's tough.

11:39.560 --> 11:41.424
- [laughs]

11:41.459 --> 11:43.288
[pleasant music]

11:43.323 --> 11:44.945
- I'm enjoying this--

11:44.980 --> 11:47.499
I'm enjoying this cold weather.

11:47.534 --> 11:50.537
♪

11:50.571 --> 11:52.988
- Boom.
- I'll tell ya.

11:53.022 --> 11:55.784
♪

11:55.818 --> 11:57.958
- Could you imagine
when people that live here,

11:57.993 --> 12:01.203
the only way to go down and up
and bring things

12:01.237 --> 12:04.033
was walking three, four hours?

12:04.068 --> 12:05.794
- I could well imagine.

12:05.828 --> 12:07.450
How long was that hike from
the funicular to here?

12:07.485 --> 12:09.556
What, four hours?
- [laughs] No, it was like--

12:09.590 --> 12:12.524
- Oh, my God, I was not sure
I was gonna make it.

12:12.559 --> 12:15.251
- Like, ten minutes, maybe 20.

12:15.286 --> 12:18.116
You're in very good shape.
Come on.

12:18.151 --> 12:19.290
This is nothing.

12:19.324 --> 12:20.429
And to eat this kind of food,

12:20.463 --> 12:22.258
we need to put some exercise
always before.

12:22.293 --> 12:23.984
- Oh, wow.

12:24.019 --> 12:25.814
♪

12:25.848 --> 12:29.127
[speaking Spanish]

12:29.162 --> 12:31.129
- What is amazing is that,

12:31.164 --> 12:33.028
if I ask you,
"What do you think this is,

12:33.062 --> 12:35.133
an appetizer,
or it's a main course?"

12:35.168 --> 12:36.169
- Right.

12:36.203 --> 12:37.515
- Many people would say,
"That's a main course."

12:37.549 --> 12:40.000
I mean, it's fatty, it's heavy.
- I would definitely say that.

12:40.035 --> 12:42.796
- Well, we eat these
in Asturias as an appetizer.

12:42.831 --> 12:44.142
The first course.

12:44.177 --> 12:45.903
- Wow. And it's fa--
[stammers]--"fabado"?

12:45.937 --> 12:47.283
- Fabada.
- "Favada."

12:47.318 --> 12:48.975
- Fabada.

12:49.009 --> 12:52.185
♪

12:52.219 --> 12:55.809
It's very difficult
to define a region by a dish,

12:55.844 --> 12:58.018
but without a doubt,

12:58.053 --> 13:00.849
Asturias is defined
by this dish.

13:00.883 --> 13:02.126
Fabada.

13:02.160 --> 13:03.886
- Deep, deep, soulful cooking.

13:03.921 --> 13:05.508
- You have to meet Guillermina.

13:05.543 --> 13:07.441
Probably she's inside.

13:07.476 --> 13:09.961
♪

13:09.996 --> 13:11.273
[slow guitar music]

13:11.307 --> 13:13.827
Guillermina's
a very special person.

13:13.862 --> 13:16.519
101 years old.

13:16.554 --> 13:18.038
Well, she is not in
the kitchen anymore,

13:18.073 --> 13:20.489
but until not too long ago,
she was.

13:20.523 --> 13:22.146
♪

13:22.180 --> 13:23.319
In this day and age,

13:23.354 --> 13:24.976
it seems that kitchens
are manned by men.

13:25.011 --> 13:27.013
We don't realize
who is feeding humanity

13:27.047 --> 13:28.635
are women.

13:28.669 --> 13:32.018
In a woman like Guillermina,
you see very much that.

13:32.052 --> 13:35.469
She's the only one that could
be up there in that place,

13:35.504 --> 13:37.264
at the end of the world,

13:37.299 --> 13:40.095
feeding the few
that will arrive there,

13:40.129 --> 13:43.063
to give them enough energy
to go back.

13:43.098 --> 13:47.896
♪

13:49.414 --> 13:52.003
[dog barking]

13:52.038 --> 13:54.661
- These beans really
are magical beans.

13:54.695 --> 13:56.456
- 'Cause they are special.
- Yeah.

13:56.490 --> 13:58.458
- Same seeds anywhere else,

13:58.492 --> 14:00.909
but they don't grow
the same way they grow here.

14:00.943 --> 14:02.082
- Mm-hmm.

14:02.117 --> 14:03.497
- It's something
about this land

14:03.532 --> 14:05.120
and the weather
and the altitude

14:05.154 --> 14:08.399
that makes these beans
very special.

14:08.433 --> 14:11.885
- Tastes like it did when it
was just little José up here

14:11.920 --> 14:14.336
in his lederhosen.

14:14.370 --> 14:15.682
- [laughs]

14:15.716 --> 14:17.304
- Tastes the same?
- Tastes the same.

14:17.339 --> 14:19.134
- You happy?
- This is as good.

14:19.168 --> 14:21.032
- I'm happy too.
- This is as good.

14:21.067 --> 14:23.138
And it's worth it.

14:23.172 --> 14:24.967
It's worth the walk.
- Mmm.

14:27.004 --> 14:29.661
[soft guitar music]

14:29.696 --> 14:32.285
- I mean, you show all of us
that it's worth it

14:32.319 --> 14:36.116
to go to the end of the world
for the right food...

14:36.151 --> 14:39.154
and for the right stories.

14:39.188 --> 14:41.328
- Well, in this case, yes.

14:41.363 --> 14:43.468
♪

14:43.503 --> 14:50.510
♪

15:03.385 --> 15:04.179
Do you know how to play
this game?

15:04.213 --> 15:06.146
- Tony, I've seen these often.

15:06.181 --> 15:08.045
I've never played in my life.

15:08.079 --> 15:09.391
♪

15:09.425 --> 15:12.532
- [speaking Spanish]

15:12.566 --> 15:14.292
♪

15:14.327 --> 15:15.569
- So it has to be
over the line?

15:15.604 --> 15:16.639
- Over the line,
very important.

15:16.674 --> 15:18.089
- Right, okay, good.

15:18.124 --> 15:19.470
- So, it has to hit that sur--
we know that.

15:19.504 --> 15:21.058
- All right.

15:21.092 --> 15:23.094
But it's okay
if you hit any pin?

15:23.129 --> 15:24.475
But it can bounce?

15:24.509 --> 15:26.235
- It can bounce, yeah. Eh?

15:26.270 --> 15:29.066
[woman speaking Spanish]

15:29.100 --> 15:32.103
So the ball has to go spinning,

15:32.138 --> 15:34.105
so when it touches,

15:34.140 --> 15:35.555
the spin will take the ball...

15:35.589 --> 15:37.350
- Right, I can do that.

15:37.384 --> 15:39.076
- Probably no.

15:39.110 --> 15:40.525
♪

15:40.560 --> 15:46.117
- [speaking Spanish]

15:46.152 --> 15:47.636
I cannot believe
this is the first time.

15:47.670 --> 15:49.086
Yeah, sí, vamonos.

15:56.196 --> 15:59.027
- Eso... cuatro!

15:59.061 --> 16:00.649
Muy bien!

16:00.683 --> 16:02.237
♪

16:02.271 --> 16:03.997
- All right. Not bad.

16:06.206 --> 16:07.690
- Try to beat that.
- Okay.

16:07.725 --> 16:11.246
[exciting guitar music]

16:11.280 --> 16:12.557
- Look it, look it...

16:12.592 --> 16:15.112
with the hand,
a little bit of a spin.

16:15.146 --> 16:16.423
[grunts]

16:16.458 --> 16:18.322
♪♪

16:18.356 --> 16:20.048
- Tres! Tres!

16:20.082 --> 16:23.085
[applause]

16:23.120 --> 16:24.086
♪

16:24.121 --> 16:26.088
- [speaks Spanish]

16:26.123 --> 16:30.506
♪

16:30.541 --> 16:32.163
Three points!

16:32.198 --> 16:38.998
♪

16:41.862 --> 16:43.140
- Ugh.

16:43.174 --> 16:45.038
This game is rigged.

16:45.073 --> 16:48.076
♪

16:48.110 --> 16:48.938
[laughs]

16:48.973 --> 16:51.320
- That was a heck
of a good shot, man.

16:51.355 --> 16:53.046
- Ah, too much.

16:53.081 --> 16:55.221
- [laughs]
His throw.

16:55.255 --> 16:57.257
- They're taking shelter.

16:57.292 --> 16:58.603
- They are?

17:05.610 --> 17:08.648
[waves crashing]

17:15.137 --> 17:17.519
- Asturias is really...

17:17.553 --> 17:19.866
to a degree,
it's land of plenty, but...

17:19.900 --> 17:22.834
[elegant string music]

17:22.869 --> 17:24.836
To a degree, it's not.

17:24.871 --> 17:26.873
♪

17:26.907 --> 17:29.531
It's not what you want
when you want it.

17:29.565 --> 17:32.603
It is when the land wants
to give it to you.

17:32.637 --> 17:35.606
The river, the mountains...

17:35.640 --> 17:38.367
the sea.

17:38.402 --> 17:40.093
You have to respect
the land first,

17:40.128 --> 17:41.750
and maybe then...

17:41.784 --> 17:44.201
the land wants
to give you something.

17:44.235 --> 17:50.897
♪

17:50.931 --> 17:54.211
Asturias, many of the
restaurants you're gonna go,

17:54.245 --> 17:55.902
you're gonna get
that feeling...

17:55.936 --> 17:57.766
♪

17:57.800 --> 17:59.319
It's something beyond

17:59.354 --> 18:00.907
just the plate you have
in front of you.

18:00.941 --> 18:04.186
♪

18:04.221 --> 18:07.534
It is the understanding of...

18:07.569 --> 18:10.227
the happiness
that hardship gives you.

18:10.261 --> 18:16.474
♪

18:28.831 --> 18:30.868
- So, we're drinking cider?

18:30.902 --> 18:33.146
- That's what we should
be drinking.

18:33.181 --> 18:35.562
- And it goes good
with the seafood?

18:35.597 --> 18:38.358
- The biggest partnership
in the history of mankind.

18:38.393 --> 18:40.222
- Wow, strong words.
- By far.

18:40.257 --> 18:41.223
Yeah.

18:41.258 --> 18:43.846
[light music]

18:43.881 --> 18:45.193
To me, this is probably

18:45.227 --> 18:48.679
one of the most difficult
things to do.

18:48.713 --> 18:52.579
Look at how he's hitting
the rim of the glass.

18:52.614 --> 18:54.512
Look at all the oxygen
that they're putting.

18:54.547 --> 18:56.928
Look at--I mean,
I love this tradition.

18:56.963 --> 18:59.897
And he doesn't even
look at the glass.

18:59.931 --> 19:02.796
Come on. He's like a Jedi.

19:02.831 --> 19:08.147
♪

19:11.322 --> 19:13.876
- [speaks Spanish]

19:13.911 --> 19:15.706
That's beautiful.

19:15.740 --> 19:18.571
- Oricios. Sea urchin.
- Yeah.

19:18.605 --> 19:21.194
♪

19:21.229 --> 19:22.989
- You know what,
I'd kill for these.

19:23.023 --> 19:24.542
- Mmm.

19:24.577 --> 19:26.579
Holy crap.

19:26.613 --> 19:27.994
♪

19:28.028 --> 19:29.927
This is one of my favorite
things on earth.

19:29.961 --> 19:32.205
Good sea urchin.
- Me too.

19:32.240 --> 19:33.517
- Mmm.

19:33.551 --> 19:36.244
- Probably this is one
of the best animals

19:36.278 --> 19:37.935
we have in the ocean.
- Right.

19:37.969 --> 19:40.627
- Oricios.
- Oricios.

19:40.662 --> 19:42.353
♪

19:42.388 --> 19:46.254
- Traditionally,
I like to eat them raw,

19:46.288 --> 19:48.290
but in Asturias, the vast
majority of the people,

19:48.325 --> 19:50.292
they like them
put into water...

19:50.327 --> 19:51.949
- Really?
- For a few seconds.

19:51.983 --> 19:53.606
This is plancha.

19:53.640 --> 19:56.229
And this is very much
the cooking of Spain,

19:56.264 --> 19:57.713
the cooking of Asturias.

19:57.748 --> 19:59.922
The seafood will be raw,

19:59.957 --> 20:01.372
will be a slightly boil,

20:01.407 --> 20:02.994
or will be done
on the flattop,

20:03.029 --> 20:04.996
quick, fast.

20:05.031 --> 20:06.377
- Right.

20:06.412 --> 20:09.242
- [speaks Spanish]

20:09.277 --> 20:11.244
- The centollo:
the spider crab.

20:11.279 --> 20:12.797
- Oh, yeah...
- Where is Instagram?

20:12.832 --> 20:13.936
- Yeah, I'm on it.
- Boom.

20:13.971 --> 20:16.042
- I'm on it, dude.
I'm getting a zoom shot.

20:16.076 --> 20:17.906
People complain
about my pans...

20:17.940 --> 20:20.253
- [laughs]
- But I'm going in for a zoom.

20:20.288 --> 20:22.255
Going in for the close.

20:22.290 --> 20:24.602
- Boom.
- Oh, yeah.

20:24.637 --> 20:26.742
- Okay, my man.

20:26.777 --> 20:27.950
♪

20:27.985 --> 20:29.711
- This...
- This is unbelievable.

20:29.745 --> 20:30.884
- Is what I'm talking about.

20:30.919 --> 20:32.576
- This is one of
the best centollos

20:32.610 --> 20:33.646
I've seen in a long time.

20:33.680 --> 20:36.925
- Oh, I mean,
it's unbelievable.

20:36.959 --> 20:39.376
- Are you smelling?
Smell this. Smell.

20:39.410 --> 20:40.446
- Yeah.

20:42.033 --> 20:44.381
- Do you understand?
This is the smell of seafood.

20:44.415 --> 20:46.072
♪

20:46.106 --> 20:48.419
Sometimes, we forget
that it doesn't matter

20:48.454 --> 20:51.629
how good is the seafood
or fresh.

20:51.664 --> 20:52.941
I don't care if it's
the catch of the day.

20:52.975 --> 20:55.944
If it's overcooked, it's gone.

20:55.978 --> 20:58.360
♪

20:58.395 --> 21:01.467
[man speaking Spanish]

21:02.847 --> 21:03.952
- We got percebes.

21:03.986 --> 21:05.540
- Gooseneck barnacles, my boy.
- Sweet!

21:05.574 --> 21:06.748
- [speaks Spanish]
- All right.

21:06.782 --> 21:08.439
- [laughs]

21:08.474 --> 21:10.061
All right.

21:10.096 --> 21:12.029
- What, we're going swimming
for those things later?

21:12.063 --> 21:13.582
- You want to?

21:13.617 --> 21:15.377
- What, do you just dive
right in with a Speedo

21:15.412 --> 21:17.621
and rip them off the wall,
right?

21:17.655 --> 21:19.692
- Yep.
- Easy.

21:19.726 --> 21:22.039
- No.
[chuckles]

21:22.073 --> 21:25.007
[stealthy percussive music]

21:25.042 --> 21:26.146
♪

21:26.181 --> 21:28.425
You have to respect
that at the sea...

21:28.459 --> 21:30.806
♪

21:30.841 --> 21:32.152
These guys put
their lives at risk

21:32.187 --> 21:35.052
to bring the fresh gooseneck
barnacles to the tables.

21:35.086 --> 21:38.952
But it's a flavor
like no other.

21:38.987 --> 21:42.956
Sometimes, I feel like, wow,
we don't appreciate enough

21:42.991 --> 21:44.924
when we eat these foods.

21:44.958 --> 21:47.996
A whole bunch goes into it.

21:48.030 --> 21:49.480
With other fishermen,

21:49.515 --> 21:51.724
we wouldn't be having
what we have.

21:51.758 --> 21:57.764
♪

21:57.799 --> 21:59.525
So you like the cider?

21:59.559 --> 22:02.459
- Yes, this is quite delicious.

22:02.493 --> 22:04.909
- You see how
apples and seafood

22:04.944 --> 22:06.359
go hand by hand?

22:06.394 --> 22:08.119
Because this is very acidic.

22:08.154 --> 22:09.880
'Cause nice acidity

22:09.914 --> 22:11.088
goes so well
with the saltiness.

22:11.122 --> 22:12.641
It's unbelievable.
It's a perfect match.

22:12.676 --> 22:16.058
- It's like ebony and ivory
living together in harmony.

22:16.093 --> 22:18.716
- [laughs]

22:18.751 --> 22:20.028
- [chuckles]

22:20.062 --> 22:22.099
- Where do you come up
with this phrase?

22:22.133 --> 22:25.033
- That's, uh,
I think Sir Paul McCartney.

22:25.067 --> 22:27.000
One of his more insipid lines.

22:30.141 --> 22:32.972
[wind whooshing]

22:36.216 --> 22:38.978
[tranquil music]

22:39.012 --> 22:42.050
♪

22:42.084 --> 22:43.879
- Well, you told me
Asturias was beautiful,

22:43.914 --> 22:46.951
but, uh, man, you didn't lie.

22:46.986 --> 22:49.540
It is amazing.

22:49.575 --> 22:51.128
I can't believe
these, like, farmhouses

22:51.162 --> 22:53.406
all the way up these mountains.

22:53.441 --> 22:55.546
- There are no farmhouses.

22:55.581 --> 22:57.928
It's where the shepherds stay

22:57.962 --> 22:59.654
for weeks at a time sometimes,

22:59.688 --> 23:01.966
taking care of the herd,

23:02.001 --> 23:04.210
of the goats, of the sheep,
of the cows.

23:04.244 --> 23:07.731
Their cheeses are made
with the three milks.

23:07.765 --> 23:12.494
♪

23:12.529 --> 23:16.222
And Asturias has the biggest
concentration of cheese makers

23:16.256 --> 23:18.017
anywhere in the world,

23:18.051 --> 23:19.605
period.

23:19.639 --> 23:22.573
♪♪

23:22.608 --> 23:25.645
And we use the land
like nobody.

23:25.680 --> 23:28.821
Especially using the caves
to cure them

23:28.855 --> 23:30.478
is brilliant.

23:30.512 --> 23:36.967
♪

23:37.001 --> 23:38.244
Not a lot of places
in the world

23:38.278 --> 23:40.073
that you have
something like this,

23:40.108 --> 23:42.110
caves that produce,

23:42.144 --> 23:44.733
for centuries, amazing cheese.

23:44.768 --> 23:48.668
♪

23:48.703 --> 23:50.152
- Do you think you could do
a cheese-themed,

23:50.187 --> 23:52.948
like, uh, theme park?

23:52.983 --> 23:54.087
- That can be fun.

23:54.122 --> 23:57.056
- A giant volcano of cheese...

23:57.090 --> 23:59.161
- [laughs]

23:59.196 --> 24:01.232
- Take little boats around
in a fondue pot.

24:01.267 --> 24:03.131
- I don't know, but you know
what I think sometimes?

24:03.165 --> 24:05.064
- Yeah?
- You know, "Apocalypse Now"...

24:05.098 --> 24:07.135
- Yes.
- When Marlon Brando--

24:07.169 --> 24:09.033
I don't remember
what was the name of the--

24:09.068 --> 24:10.656
- Kurtz. Colonel Kurtz.
- Yeah!

24:10.690 --> 24:12.796
- Walter E. Kurtz.
- And they finally find him...

24:12.830 --> 24:14.660
- Right. Right.
- Living in that cave?

24:14.694 --> 24:16.006
I always dreamed,
like, one day,

24:16.040 --> 24:17.628
I'm good gonna end
in a place like this...

24:17.663 --> 24:18.940
- But just surrounded by chee--
it'll be a cheese cave.

24:18.974 --> 24:21.563
- Surrounded by cheese
and living alone.

24:21.598 --> 24:23.496
And maybe one day,
my friend Eric Ripert

24:23.531 --> 24:25.498
and Tony Bourdain visited me,

24:25.533 --> 24:27.811
before I lose control
of my mind.

24:27.845 --> 24:29.640
- So, wait a minute,
I'm seeing this.

24:29.675 --> 24:31.849
You're dressed all in black.
We shave your head.

24:31.884 --> 24:33.920
You're sitting in
this dark cheese cave.

24:33.955 --> 24:35.853
Eric Ripert playing
Corporal Willard

24:35.888 --> 24:37.027
comes to kill you.

24:37.061 --> 24:39.167
Finds you surrounded by
all of these fantastic cheeses.

24:39.201 --> 24:41.997
I'd play the Dennis Hopper
role, of course.

24:42.032 --> 24:42.998
- It's gonna happen.

24:43.033 --> 24:45.000
I see it happening.

24:45.035 --> 24:48.107
[Richard Wagner's
"Ride of the Valkyries"]

24:48.141 --> 24:51.213
[indistinct radio chatter]

24:51.248 --> 24:55.321
♪

24:55.355 --> 24:57.668
- You ever seen a snail

24:57.703 --> 25:00.740
crawl across the edge
of a straight razor?

25:00.775 --> 25:07.816
♪

25:11.061 --> 25:13.304
- I can just see Eric now,
dressed in fatigue, saying,

25:13.339 --> 25:16.031
"They said your methods
are unsound."

25:17.861 --> 25:19.241
- Man, why do you always
finish your beer

25:19.276 --> 25:21.002
and I barely begin?

25:21.036 --> 25:23.073
- [sighs]
Professional.

25:23.107 --> 25:25.109
I'm seriously liking
this cheese.

25:25.144 --> 25:27.629
You export these, right?

25:27.664 --> 25:29.735
- Spain, oh, yeah, big exports.
- Yeah.

25:29.769 --> 25:31.909
- Like, this one is Cabrales,
which always was my favorite.

25:31.944 --> 25:34.084
- But that is, like,
super funky, right?

25:34.118 --> 25:36.017
- Cabrales? I love it.

25:36.051 --> 25:38.295
I do really love Cabrales.

25:38.329 --> 25:40.331
- This is really lovely.
This is fantastic.

25:40.366 --> 25:43.749
It just all depends on how far
into the funk zone you go.

25:43.783 --> 25:45.267
- And look at--look at--
look at--look at this.

25:45.302 --> 25:48.305
It's almost, like,
green--green-bluish.

25:48.339 --> 25:50.963
It's almost like
the sky and the grass

25:50.997 --> 25:53.172
are touching each other
right on the cheese.

25:53.206 --> 25:55.105
I mean...

25:55.139 --> 25:57.625
And you know one thing,
it's full of penicillin, man.

25:57.659 --> 25:59.661
Nobody gets ever sick,

25:59.696 --> 26:01.663
if you really eat
these cheeses.

26:01.698 --> 26:04.010
- I feel my syphilis
clearing up.

26:05.874 --> 26:08.325
- [snorting, laughing]

26:10.879 --> 26:12.398
[smooth instrumental music]

26:12.432 --> 26:13.917
Man!

26:13.951 --> 26:15.677
All right, cut!

26:15.712 --> 26:22.373
♪

26:26.032 --> 26:27.137
- So please explain to me...

26:29.208 --> 26:32.107
This gentlemen caught
the fish last year.

26:32.142 --> 26:32.970
Is that correct?

26:33.005 --> 26:34.972
- 2014.

26:35.007 --> 26:38.044
- In 2014, you go--
[speaks Spanish]

26:38.079 --> 26:40.357
- So, that means, what,
the first salmon

26:40.391 --> 26:42.152
caught on the river.

26:42.186 --> 26:43.291
- El campano.

26:43.325 --> 26:45.983
The first salmon of the season.

26:46.018 --> 26:48.158
Yeah. Campano.

26:49.711 --> 26:52.231
[ethereal music]

26:52.265 --> 26:55.096
Today, for the entire day,

26:55.130 --> 26:57.339
around the rivers of Asturias,

26:57.374 --> 27:00.273
hundreds of fishermen
trying to get the permit

27:00.308 --> 27:02.068
in a kind of an auction,

27:02.103 --> 27:05.037
in a kind of a lottery,

27:05.071 --> 27:07.660
where they are gonna
grant them

27:07.695 --> 27:09.282
certain parts of the river...
- Right.

27:09.317 --> 27:12.009
- And only for 30 minutes,

27:12.044 --> 27:13.079
one hour at a time,

27:13.114 --> 27:16.013
depending how many fishermen
show up.

27:16.048 --> 27:17.981
- Siete.

27:18.015 --> 27:19.016
- No commercial fishermen?

27:19.051 --> 27:21.053
- [speaks Spanish]

27:21.087 --> 27:22.882
- Only the campano.

27:22.917 --> 27:29.924
♪

27:33.099 --> 27:34.963
- The old days,

27:34.998 --> 27:37.690
salmon was plentiful.

27:37.725 --> 27:40.037
And the first salmon
is called el campano,

27:40.072 --> 27:43.316
and el campano means,
really, from the bells

27:43.351 --> 27:47.113
that will ring on the churches

27:47.148 --> 27:51.083
near the river
where the salmon was caught,

27:51.117 --> 27:54.362
not as a celebration
of the salmon,

27:54.396 --> 27:57.123
but as a way to tell everybody

27:57.158 --> 27:59.160
that salmons are back.

27:59.194 --> 28:02.335
"Let's go back to the river
and fish them,

28:02.370 --> 28:05.373
'cause that is the food
we are waiting for."

28:05.407 --> 28:08.031
♪

28:11.103 --> 28:12.967
I get super emotional
when I think--

28:13.001 --> 28:14.520
take a look
at all these photos.

28:14.554 --> 28:17.178
I remember watching
those same photos

28:17.212 --> 28:20.457
of my grandfather
hunting and fishing

28:20.491 --> 28:22.148
and catching salmons,

28:22.183 --> 28:24.254
and this to me,
being here in this moment,

28:24.288 --> 28:26.049
becomes really personal.

28:26.083 --> 28:28.810
- I hear a rumor you're looking
to buy a fish today?

28:28.845 --> 28:30.812
You're looking to bid
on the first?

28:30.847 --> 28:32.987
- Listen to me:
Bourdain and Andrés.

28:33.021 --> 28:34.333
- What, you're looking
to get me in on this too?

28:34.367 --> 28:36.162
- B and A. El campano.

28:36.197 --> 28:38.268
Between you and me,
we can afford it, no?

28:38.302 --> 28:39.510
- All right, I'm in, I'm in.

28:39.545 --> 28:41.892
I'm in for 50% of this fish.

28:41.927 --> 28:44.308
Now, what's the
highest price paid

28:44.343 --> 28:46.034
for the first fish
of the season?

28:46.069 --> 28:49.037
- For a campano, it means
6,000, 7,000, 8,000?

28:49.072 --> 28:50.280
- 18--

28:50.314 --> 28:53.076
18, uh, euros.

28:53.110 --> 28:55.837
- 18? Diez y ocho?
Diez y ocho?

28:55.872 --> 28:57.183
- 18,000 euros?
- 18,000!

28:57.218 --> 28:59.151
- I'm out.
- [laughs]

28:59.185 --> 29:02.154
- Some local guy is
gonna jack the price,

29:02.188 --> 29:03.155
and he's gonna keep bidding

29:03.189 --> 29:04.812
until you're up to, like, 22.

29:04.846 --> 29:06.158
- Come on, Tony Bourdain,
what are you talking about?

29:06.192 --> 29:07.538
What are you doing
with your money?

29:07.573 --> 29:09.782
- What am I gonna do with
the fish? I can't keep it.

29:09.817 --> 29:11.508
- We're gonna--come on,
we're gonna eat it.

29:11.542 --> 29:12.751
You know?

29:14.545 --> 29:15.754
- Damn.

29:17.514 --> 29:18.998
It's a lot of money.

29:21.242 --> 29:22.899
- Tony...

29:24.452 --> 29:25.487
- They are delicious.

29:25.522 --> 29:28.387
- [laughs]

29:28.421 --> 29:30.354
No, let's do it.
- All right.

29:30.389 --> 29:31.390
I mean, what else
do we got here?

29:31.424 --> 29:33.012
- We're gonna eat
plenty of food.

29:40.917 --> 29:43.160
- You know, Tony...
[chuckles]

29:46.232 --> 29:47.509
Tony's Tony.

29:49.477 --> 29:52.100
[soft guitar music]

29:52.135 --> 29:53.826
It's easy to love Tony.

29:53.861 --> 29:55.034
♪

29:55.069 --> 29:57.105
He's a good guy.

29:57.140 --> 29:59.521
♪♪

29:59.556 --> 30:02.283
Super shy.

30:02.317 --> 30:04.492
That's why I believe sometimes
the side of Tony

30:04.526 --> 30:06.839
that people don't even know.

30:06.874 --> 30:09.324
♪

30:09.359 --> 30:13.190
He seems like he doesn't care
about anything...

30:13.225 --> 30:14.502
but himself...

30:14.536 --> 30:16.331
♪

30:16.366 --> 30:18.126
But then you can see it...

30:18.161 --> 30:21.026
♪♪

30:21.060 --> 30:24.098
He's the most caring person
I've ever met.

30:24.132 --> 30:26.479
♪

30:26.514 --> 30:29.206
That's why I'm happy and proud
to call him a friend.

30:29.241 --> 30:32.382
♪

30:34.591 --> 30:37.421
[indistinct chatter]

31:12.353 --> 31:15.114
[slow pizzicato music]

31:15.149 --> 31:17.013
♪

31:17.047 --> 31:20.326
- I wonder...

31:20.361 --> 31:22.087
where José is.

31:24.434 --> 31:29.059
♪

31:29.094 --> 31:30.336
- Oh, yeah.

31:30.371 --> 31:32.200
♪

31:32.235 --> 31:34.202
Ah, my hair!

31:34.237 --> 31:35.686
♪

31:35.721 --> 31:38.172
- Hope he's getting some rest.

31:38.206 --> 31:39.345
♪

31:39.380 --> 31:42.348
[waves crashing]

31:42.383 --> 31:49.286
♪

31:56.569 --> 31:58.226
- This is nuts.

31:58.261 --> 32:02.196
♪

32:02.230 --> 32:04.232
Oh, well.

32:04.267 --> 32:07.235
[birds chirping]

32:07.270 --> 32:10.238
[light percussive music]

32:10.273 --> 32:16.935
♪

32:21.698 --> 32:23.527
- Enjoy.
- Wow.

32:23.562 --> 32:26.254
Okay, so, a traditional
local dish, I guess?

32:26.289 --> 32:28.532
- Yeah, this is.
- What's this called?

32:28.567 --> 32:30.983
- Well, I think that's
pinto de caballo...

32:31.018 --> 32:32.191
- Right.
- Pinto with rice.

32:32.226 --> 32:33.054
- Ah, all right.

32:35.056 --> 32:37.541
So, born and bred in Asturias?

32:37.576 --> 32:40.027
You were born here?
- Yes, yes, yes.

32:40.061 --> 32:41.718
- What did your family--
what--what--

32:41.752 --> 32:44.100
what business
was your family in?

32:44.134 --> 32:46.585
- Well, my grandparents
were all in the mine,

32:46.619 --> 32:48.207
my mother in a little shop,

32:48.242 --> 32:50.140
and my father a teacher.

32:50.175 --> 32:51.693
- What are the typical
characteristics

32:51.728 --> 32:53.040
of someone from Asturias?

32:53.074 --> 32:55.145
Okay, independent? Tough?

32:55.180 --> 32:58.183
- Well, there is--
another sentence is:

32:58.217 --> 33:01.151
"Asturiano: borracho, loco,
y mal cristiano"...

33:01.186 --> 33:02.359
- Drunk, crazy, and Christian.

33:02.394 --> 33:04.120
- Asturia: drunk, crazy,
and bad Christian.

33:04.154 --> 33:05.362
That is important.
[laughs]

33:05.397 --> 33:09.159
- So, fair to say
a tradition of independence?

33:09.194 --> 33:11.092
- Yes.
Before the Spanish Civil War,

33:11.127 --> 33:13.094
we have
the Asturian Revolution,

33:13.129 --> 33:15.338
that Asturias do in one month.

33:15.372 --> 33:18.651
Was independent,

33:18.686 --> 33:21.551
because we have a communist,
anarchist revolution...

33:21.585 --> 33:22.655
- Mm-hmm.

33:22.690 --> 33:25.348
- The worker movement here
was massive.

33:25.382 --> 33:27.660
- In the mines?
- In the--yeah...

33:27.695 --> 33:30.077
- Mostly coming out of mines
and organized labor?

33:30.111 --> 33:32.079
- Yes, but, of course,

33:32.113 --> 33:33.735
worker class fight is over.

33:33.770 --> 33:35.772
They win.

33:35.806 --> 33:37.498
We lose.

33:37.532 --> 33:40.501
[men humming]

33:40.535 --> 33:45.092
♪

33:45.126 --> 33:48.095
[all singing in Spanish]

33:48.129 --> 33:50.407
♪

33:50.442 --> 33:51.581
The problem with the miners,

33:51.615 --> 33:54.722
it starts when
the Soviet Union was over,

33:54.756 --> 33:58.726
and then in Europe,
the social democracy...

33:58.760 --> 34:00.314
was over.

34:00.348 --> 34:02.661
And the last strike
was five years ago.

34:02.695 --> 34:09.185
♪

34:09.219 --> 34:11.221
The miners were
the last soldiers

34:11.256 --> 34:12.878
of the worker class movement.

34:12.912 --> 34:16.226
♪

34:16.261 --> 34:17.779
In the last strike,

34:17.814 --> 34:20.230
the airport was closed
by the miners,

34:20.265 --> 34:23.613
the highway, the city too.

34:23.647 --> 34:26.133
They closed Asturias.

34:26.167 --> 34:29.205
Everybody in the streets,
like, screaming.

34:29.239 --> 34:31.241
♪

34:31.276 --> 34:34.348
The miners stay in the fight,

34:34.382 --> 34:37.765
and the war is over
when one side win.

34:37.799 --> 34:39.560
♪

34:39.594 --> 34:40.906
They win...

34:40.940 --> 34:42.666
♪

34:42.701 --> 34:44.323
We lose.

34:44.358 --> 34:46.463
♪

34:49.949 --> 34:51.917
And for me, that was,
like, the end of the...

34:51.951 --> 34:53.367
- The end of organized labor.

34:53.401 --> 34:56.853
- Yeah, the end of
the worker class left.

34:56.887 --> 34:59.511
- But still you're here.
- Yeah.

34:59.545 --> 35:01.513
- The war is over,
but you're here.

35:01.547 --> 35:04.136
- Well, you can create
some money,

35:04.171 --> 35:06.932
some conditions to survive,

35:06.966 --> 35:09.728
but not a proper job.

35:09.762 --> 35:12.731
[solemn bagpipe music]

35:12.765 --> 35:15.354
♪

35:15.389 --> 35:18.392
The only way to make money
for me was play music...

35:18.426 --> 35:20.394
♪

35:20.428 --> 35:23.362
So now I'm a musician.

35:23.397 --> 35:25.157
♪

35:25.192 --> 35:28.402
I think that for my music...

35:28.436 --> 35:30.749
it's good to stay here.

35:30.783 --> 35:34.408
♪

35:34.442 --> 35:37.859
Here, I have the tools.

35:37.894 --> 35:40.241
For me,
that is very important.

35:40.276 --> 35:42.899
♪

35:42.933 --> 35:45.177
- I just heard bagpipes.

35:45.212 --> 35:46.937
Have you been invaded
by Scotland?

35:46.972 --> 35:51.287
- Well, we are one of
the eight Celtic nations.

35:51.321 --> 35:54.635
[singing in Spanish]

35:54.669 --> 35:58.225
With Wales, Bretaña, France,
and Scotland and Ireland,

35:58.259 --> 35:59.881
we are Celtic nations.

35:59.916 --> 36:02.919
♪

36:02.953 --> 36:06.543
Here, there is a kind of song
that is called tornada,

36:06.578 --> 36:09.615
and tornada is just
voice and bagpipe...

36:09.650 --> 36:12.618
♪

36:12.653 --> 36:14.206
And it's, like,
the music from the people

36:14.241 --> 36:15.863
who work with the cows...

36:15.897 --> 36:17.934
- Right, folk songs.
- Yeah, folk songs.

36:17.968 --> 36:20.626
♪

36:20.661 --> 36:23.595
I think that music
is about identity.

36:23.629 --> 36:26.391
I spend a lot of time
with my grandparents...

36:26.425 --> 36:28.393
♪

36:28.427 --> 36:31.637
They listen to
a lot of Celtic music.

36:31.672 --> 36:34.433
♪

36:34.468 --> 36:38.368
I have the life
to live that kind of music

36:38.403 --> 36:40.853
and discover my identity.

36:40.888 --> 36:42.993
And I think that Celtic,
the spirit of freedom,

36:43.028 --> 36:46.411
is part of Asturias' identity.

36:46.445 --> 36:53.452
♪

37:02.461 --> 37:05.499
[waves crashing]

37:12.920 --> 37:15.474
- Okay, we do another shot
or what?

37:15.509 --> 37:17.027
- Oh-ho-ho-ho.

37:17.062 --> 37:18.926
- Yeah, we should do
another shot.

37:21.515 --> 37:23.033
- You don't have to do it.
- I'll do it, I'll do it.

37:23.068 --> 37:24.897
- Good.

37:24.932 --> 37:26.589
Boom.

37:29.523 --> 37:30.834
[exhales sharply]

37:32.767 --> 37:36.081
- Oh... yeah.

37:36.115 --> 37:38.739
- [laughs]
That's orujo.

37:38.773 --> 37:40.361
- I've tasted this
in one form or another

37:40.396 --> 37:42.087
all over the world.
- [laughs]

37:42.121 --> 37:44.814
That's the local moonshine.
[chuckles]

37:44.848 --> 37:46.471
- That's--that's good.

37:46.505 --> 37:50.060
- Tony, I have a surprise
for you.

37:50.095 --> 37:53.029
- You finally got a salmon?

37:53.063 --> 37:54.444
- Don't move.

37:54.479 --> 37:55.997
[cheery piano music]

37:56.032 --> 37:57.309
[objects clatter]

37:57.344 --> 38:01.624
[speaking Spanish]

38:05.006 --> 38:07.077
We searched for it,
and we found it.

38:07.112 --> 38:09.079
- The magical salmon.

38:09.114 --> 38:11.392
For 1,000 euros a bite.

38:11.427 --> 38:13.739
- No! This one was given to me.

38:13.774 --> 38:15.741
- [laughs]

38:15.776 --> 38:17.916
- They got somebody
that got a salmon.

38:17.950 --> 38:19.711
♪

38:19.745 --> 38:20.919
He's super generous.

38:20.953 --> 38:23.715
He said, "You know,
you want salmon? Here."

38:23.749 --> 38:27.097
Friends feed friends.

38:27.132 --> 38:28.306
It's no way
that you come to Asturias

38:28.340 --> 38:30.929
and you go without the bite
of the salmon.

38:30.963 --> 38:34.760
♪

38:34.795 --> 38:36.106
This is gonna surprise you,

38:36.141 --> 38:38.833
because usually,
everybody always said,

38:38.868 --> 38:41.457
"The fish,
we need to grill it whole."

38:41.491 --> 38:43.044
- Right.

38:43.079 --> 38:46.047
- He breaks the fish
in pieces.

38:46.082 --> 38:47.635
He cuts all the pieces
through. Why?

38:47.670 --> 38:49.810
- Grills them separately.
- Separately.

38:49.844 --> 38:51.915
And over the flesh,

38:51.950 --> 38:54.573
because the skin
is full of fat,

38:54.608 --> 38:56.748
and you don't want
that fat to burn.

38:56.782 --> 38:58.370
You want that fat to melt.

38:58.405 --> 39:00.130
- To stay inside,
in the Spanish way.

39:00.165 --> 39:01.891
♪

39:01.925 --> 39:06.136
- And you want to maintain
the integrity of the skin.

39:06.171 --> 39:09.450
So he grills the fish
over the flesh,

39:09.485 --> 39:12.039
and then, probably, the skin...

39:12.073 --> 39:14.144
is better
than the flesh itself.

39:14.179 --> 39:17.147
- Mm.
- It's unbelievable.

39:17.182 --> 39:18.977
- Muy bien. Gracias.

39:19.011 --> 39:21.151
Buen provecho.

39:21.186 --> 39:22.981
- Oh, my God.

39:25.604 --> 39:27.019
- Wow.

39:29.194 --> 39:31.438
Mmm. Wow.

39:31.472 --> 39:32.887
- It's everything I told you?

39:32.922 --> 39:34.958
- It's everything you told me.

39:34.993 --> 39:37.789
The fats,
ethereally suspended somehow

39:37.823 --> 39:39.963
between skin, flesh, and bone.

39:39.998 --> 39:40.964
- Boom.

39:40.999 --> 39:42.621
- You bite into it,

39:42.656 --> 39:45.797
and just a flood of flavor
explodes into your brain, man.

39:45.831 --> 39:47.074
- Keep going, keep going,
keep going.

39:47.108 --> 39:49.559
- José, this is
an enchanted country,

39:49.594 --> 39:51.596
and, in fact,
this region of the country

39:51.630 --> 39:53.425
is the most extraordinary
place I--I--I...

39:53.460 --> 39:55.116
- Give me the dollar.
Where are the dollars?

39:55.151 --> 39:56.497
Dollar bill.

39:56.532 --> 39:57.981
- The mountains, the sea,

39:58.016 --> 39:59.742
it's--it's amazing.

39:59.776 --> 40:01.053
- Yes, I'm throwing you
the bills.

40:01.088 --> 40:02.917
If I had hundreds!
[laughs]

40:02.952 --> 40:05.126
- Just stuff it
in the G-string, my friend.

40:05.161 --> 40:07.128
- [laughs]

40:07.163 --> 40:08.958
♪

40:08.992 --> 40:10.994
We are so close
to a white guy, I love it.

40:11.029 --> 40:13.997
[both laugh]

40:14.032 --> 40:15.758
♪

40:15.792 --> 40:17.656
- Okay, no,
I'll let you say it.

40:17.691 --> 40:18.795
- No. [laughs]
- What do we say about now?

40:18.830 --> 40:21.591
Well, no, no, first we take
one more satisfying bite.

40:21.626 --> 40:22.799
This is how it works, okay.

40:22.834 --> 40:25.561
- I think I got the bone
in my throat.

40:25.595 --> 40:27.632
- Tracheotomy. I'm coming.
[both chuckle]

40:27.666 --> 40:30.013
I think we've learned
something here in Asturias.

40:30.048 --> 40:32.222
I don't know why I didn't
expect it to be this beautiful,

40:32.257 --> 40:35.502
but it is far more beautiful
than I could've ever imagined.

40:35.536 --> 40:37.055
The food is incredible,
the people are wonderful.

40:37.089 --> 40:39.160
You were right about
[...] everything.

40:39.195 --> 40:40.645
You call it, my friend.

40:40.679 --> 40:42.957
Turn to the camera
and say the magic word.

40:42.992 --> 40:44.994
- I am not Anthony Bourdain,

40:45.028 --> 40:46.996
but I'm calling, wide.

40:47.030 --> 40:49.032
[cackles]

40:49.067 --> 40:50.931
That's the end of the show.

40:50.965 --> 40:53.761
[laughter]

40:59.215 --> 41:01.976
[waves washing]

41:07.879 --> 41:10.847
[atmospheric music]

41:10.882 --> 41:17.820
♪

41:34.319 --> 41:40.118
♪

41:50.991 --> 41:57.031
♪
